to conduct manuals via puritan polemic and popular ballads, the collection offers a new view of the senses in early modern England.The volume offers dedicated essays on each of the five senses, each relating works of art to their cultural moments, whilst elsewhere the volume considers the senses collectively in particular cultural contexts. It also pursues the sensory experiences that early modern subjects encountered through the very acts of engaging with texts, performances and artworks. This book will appeal to scholars of early modern literature and culture, to those working in sensory studies, and to anyone interested in the art and life of early modern England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTechnology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aEnglish Renaissance.  aHesperides.  aJoachim-Ernst Berendt.  aLove melancholy.  aRobert Herrick.  aaesthetic sensory experiences.  aearly modern England.  asenses.  asensory hierarchies.  asexual excitement.  avisual clues.1 aAugust, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDecamp, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugan, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEschenbaum, Natalie K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin, Aurélie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarim-Cooper, Farah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenny, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenny, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 